node.text: Who has caught a shoal bass before?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'MEET THE SHOAL BASS'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says 'WHAT ARE THEY? They're native to the Southeastern US, and are the official Georgia State Riverine Sport Fish. Because shoal bass spend their days fighting currents in the shoals of rivers, they're one of the strongest black bass species!'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says 'HISTORY As early as the 1940's, anglers acknowledged the shoal bass as its own species. But it was officially recognized as a specieÈ in 1999. Once recognized, the shoa bass was able to be properly protected. Without an officia name, it could risk disappearing forever.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'IDENTIFICATION Color: Anywhere from olive to black Pattern: 10-15 vertical blotches Eye Color: Red World Record: 8 lbs, 12 oz Closest Relative: Spotted Bass'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'LOCATION They are historically found in the Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flin River Basin. Flint River Now, the biggest populations are in the relatively undammed Flint River as well as lakes like Blackshear.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says 'AT RISK? Dredging and damming of rivers has ruined a lot of their habitat. And competition from other bass species have also put them at risk. Thankfully the removal of some dams and added fishing regulations are helping the Shoal Bass survive!'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'FISHING Fly fishing is a common technique for Shoals, since they're often in the fast-moving currents of rivers. They like to hold tight to rocks, and are known to strike hard, jump high, and put up a great fight!'.
Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Karen: Did you know this is a private pond? The law requires that I answer "no"'.

node.text: It's awesome to see a ton of people out fishing! But it can make the bite tough. What tips do you use on pressured water?⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3 PRESSURED WATER TIPS'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'a STAND OUT Pressured water or high pressure from other anglers, is when there are lot of people fishing in one place. "I have seen this same jig 5 times today.. This means fish are seeing the same baits all day, and may stop biting them. Stand out by using baits no one else is using, or aren't as popular. Also, try mixing up your presentation.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says '2. EXPLORE Avoid the crowds and pressure by getting on the water early morning or fishing at night. Also, explore the area and go to hard to reach places other people won't go to, like the backs of creeks or small pockets. It doesn't have to be perfect, just has to be isolated.'.

Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3. DOWNSIZE In pressured water fish often avoid chunkier baits, and prefer smaller more finesse style baits. Slowing down or speeding up your retrieve can also help. Remember to try different retrieve speeds before changing lures or locations.'.
Photo by Karl’s Bait & Tackle on September 12, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'You smallmouth fishing Not catching footballs Your Fantasy Football team KARL'S Bait & Tackle THE CATCH'.
